Vexor vex_crypto — Third-Party Attributions
===========================================

Vexor runs a self-contained, FFI-free-capable, pure-Zig cryptographic stack.
Several components are Vexor's own implementations that are INFORMED BY, and in
places SUBSTANTIALLY ADAPTED FROM, prior Apache-2.0 open-source work. We do not
claim to be the first pure-Zig Solana crypto implementation — Syndica's Sig
already ships one, and we credit it below. What Vexor contributes is the
integration: a decoupled, standalone, byte-exact stack gated against the live
cluster and tuned for our hot paths.

This NOTICE covers the Ed25519 subtree specifically (Phase 1 of the pure-Zig
crypto rewrite, 2026-07-11). Other components (BN254, Poseidon, BLS12-381,
BLAKE3, LtHash) carry their own attributions where applicable.


1. Ed25519 — src/vex_crypto/ed25519/
------------------------------------

The Ed25519 subtree is TWO layers, and this NOTICE credits them precisely:

  OURS (Vexor-authored orchestration + API — src/vex_crypto/ed25519/root.zig):
    the double-base scalar-multiply (`doubleBaseMul`), the w-NAF machinery
    (`asNaf`) and NAF lookup tables, the three explicitly-named verify
    predicates and the verify-strictness matrix, `signPureZig`, and
    `verifyBatchStrict`. The consensus `verify()` path (src/vex_crypto/
    ed25519.zig) is deliberately bare `std.crypto.sign.Ed25519` — never routed
    through this subtree. This layer is Vexor's own; it is informed by Sig's
    ed25519.zig (which in turn credits the dalek-cryptography curve25519-dalek
    IFMA backend, https://github.com/dalek-cryptography/curve25519-dalek,
    BSD/Apache), but it is not a verbatim copy — the API shape, the strictness
    matrix, and the sign path are Vexor's.

  CREDITED FLOOR (the field-element + point vector kernels — avx512.zig,
  generic.zig): these are carried as the verbatim numeric floor, credited, and
  NOT claimed as from-scratch — exactly analogous to the fiat-crypto artifact
  used for BN254. They are the dalek-cryptography curve25519-dalek vectorized
  IFMA algorithm at the bit level (canonical RFC8032 curve25519 arithmetic);
  there is no cleaner byte-identical expression, so re-writing them would be
  cosmetic churn with real fork risk and zero honesty gain, and they sit only
  on the drop-safe shred path — so they are kept and credited, not re-authored.
  Reached here via Syndica's Sig client:
    Project : Sig
    Source  : https://github.com/syndica/sig
    License : Apache License 2.0
    Files   : lib/crypto/ed25519/avx512.zig
              lib/crypto/ed25519/generic.zig
              lib/crypto/ed25519/wycheproof.zig  (Google Wycheproof KAT corpus)

  * avx512.zig  — the AVX-512 IFMA (vpmadd52) parallel field-element backend
    (ExtendedPoint / CachedPoint over @Vector(4,u64) 52-bit limbs). Carried
    substantially verbatim; the math is unchanged. Verified to BUILD AND PASS
    on Zig 0.15.2 under -mcpu=znver4 (Sig's own header warned the vpmadd52
    intrinsic crashed LLVM on Zig 0.14.1 — that does NOT reproduce on 0.15.2).
  * generic.zig — the portable AVX2-generalized @Vector field backend used as
    the automatic fallback when the target lacks avx512ifma+avx512vl. Carried
    substantially verbatim.
  * wycheproof.zig — Project Wycheproof EDDSA test vectors (generated data),
    carried verbatim as a KAT corpus. Wycheproof is Google's, Apache-2.0.

  NOTE: Sig's general N-point multi-scalar-mul (straus.zig / pippenger.zig) was
  briefly vendored during Phase 1 but is NOT part of this stack: the ed25519
  verify path uses the 2-point `doubleBaseMul`, and the one in-tree MSM
  consumer (the zk-ElGamal proof program) carries its own std.crypto.ecc-based
  implementation (src/vex_bpf2/zksdk/ed25519.zig). We do not ship unused
  vendored code, so those two files were removed.

HOW WE DECOUPLED IT (made it standalone + our own):
  * Removed every Sig-internal namespace dependency: the `sig.*` /
    `lib.solana.Signature` / `lib.solana.Pubkey` / `build-options` imports and
    the `common` self-referential module. The subtree compiles with only
    `std` — no Sig build graph needed.
  * Reshaped the public API to Vexor's call-site contract: our verifiers take
    raw wire bytes (`*const [64]u8` sig, `*const [32]u8` pubkey, `[]const u8`
    message) instead of Sig's `Signature`/`Pubkey` structs, matching the shape
    of the Firedancer Ballet FFI they replace.
  * Reconciled the verify-strictness matrix against Vexor's already-live
    consensus routing (the proven fork class at slot 415479361). We expose
    THREE explicitly-named predicates and DELIBERATELY do NOT route the
    consensus path through the Sig-derived ones:
      - consensus verify()  = std.crypto.sign.Ed25519 (cofactored, Agave/dalek/
        cluster-equivalent) — UNCHANGED, never touched by this subtree.
      - verifyStrict()       = exact + full low-order rejection (== Firedancer
        Ballet fd_ed25519_verify == dalek verify_strict) — used on the
        drop-safe shred path only.
      - verifyLenientCofactorless() = Sig's cofactorless verify, exposed for
        audited comparison; NOT wired to consensus.
    A 3-way KAT matrix (ed25519/kat.zig) pins these verdicts as a regression
    guard, including the cofactored cases where the consensus predicate accepts
    but both Sig-derived predicates reject.
  * Added Vexor-owned sign (signPureZig), KAT-proven byte-identical to
    std.crypto's RFC 8032 signing, built on our own doubleBaseMul.


2. Firedancer Ballet — differential oracle (not vendored into this subtree)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Project : Firedancer
    Source  : https://github.com/firedancer-io/firedancer
    License : Apache License 2.0

During development, Ballet's fd_ed25519_verify / fd_ed25519_sign (AVX-512 C)
were linked behind a -Dballet_ed25519 build flag and used as a differential
ORACLE: the ed25519/kat.zig differential KAT proved our pure-Zig verifyStrict
agreed with fd_ed25519_verify byte-for-byte on canonical vectors. That FFI
backend was removed entirely on 2026-07-12 once the epoch-boundary soak
passed — Vexor's ed25519 is unconditionally pure-Zig today; the KAT corpus
remains as a regression guard against the recorded Ballet-verified vectors.


3. Agave / Solana Labs — reference semantics
--------------------------------------------
    Project : Agave (Solana validator)
    Source  : https://github.com/anza-xyz/agave
    License : Apache License 2.0

Agave is the consensus ground truth. The consensus verify() path deliberately
matches Agave/dalek acceptance semantics (via std.crypto). The precompile
strictness (SIMD-0152, Agave 4.2) is handled separately in
src/vex_crypto/ed25519_precompile.zig and is out of scope for this subtree.


